WEBVTT

00:00:13.140 --> 00:00:16.260
Hi everybody, welcome to WWDC.

00:00:16.260 --> 00:00:19.430
My name is Alan Cannistraro,
I'm the engineering manager for iBooks.

00:00:19.570 --> 00:00:25.920
And today we're going to teach you how
to make beautiful books using HTML5,

00:00:25.960 --> 00:00:28.300
CSS3 and EPUB.

00:00:28.300 --> 00:00:32.960
We're going to show you how to take your
books far beyond what you can do in print

00:00:33.330 --> 00:00:35.500
and add features like audio and video.

00:00:35.640 --> 00:00:37.860
We'll talk about how to add animation.

00:00:37.900 --> 00:00:42.700
And at the end of the talk today,
we're going to show you a feature that

00:00:42.710 --> 00:00:46.300
nobody has seen before with iBooks 1.3.

00:00:46.510 --> 00:00:50.530
Before we dive in,
let me talk about books for a moment.

00:00:51.500 --> 00:00:54.010
Books have been around
for thousands of years.

00:00:54.230 --> 00:00:55.940
They were invented by the Romans.

00:00:56.240 --> 00:00:58.170
They are

00:00:58.500 --> 00:01:01.120
A record of our human history.

00:01:01.120 --> 00:01:05.110
They're a collection of all
of our accumulated knowledge.

00:01:05.330 --> 00:01:07.330
A book can tell a story.

00:01:07.520 --> 00:01:09.700
It can take you to another world.

00:01:10.070 --> 00:01:15.680
Books have changed the course of history,
politics and religion.

00:01:15.760 --> 00:01:20.080
A good book is engaging
and hard to put down.

00:01:21.830 --> 00:01:27.130
The last innovation with books
was 650 years ago when Gutenberg

00:01:27.130 --> 00:01:30.460
invented the printing press and
brought books to the masses.

00:01:30.580 --> 00:01:34.780
Well, in the last two years,
we've seen something very new

00:01:34.890 --> 00:01:39.240
and that's the advent of digital
books on devices like the iPad,

00:01:39.470 --> 00:01:42.380
the iPhone and the iPod Touch.

00:01:42.530 --> 00:01:46.440
Now, people can take thousands of
books with them in their pocket

00:01:46.440 --> 00:01:50.840
or in their bags and they can read
them anywhere they want to go.

00:01:50.960 --> 00:01:55.180
We're going to show you today
how to make these books.

00:01:55.290 --> 00:01:58.170
So let's talk about
digital books for a moment.

00:01:59.050 --> 00:02:02.950
This is a graph of the digital book
market over the last nine years.

00:02:03.190 --> 00:02:05.880
As you can see,
digital books were around about

00:02:06.160 --> 00:02:09.420
nine years ago and even before,
but it wasn't until the last

00:02:09.420 --> 00:02:12.880
year or two that we've actually
started to see this take off.

00:02:13.930 --> 00:02:18.160
But in 2011,
the digital book market is expected

00:02:18.160 --> 00:02:21.900
to grow to one billion dollars.

00:02:23.970 --> 00:02:29.190
Anyway, so... Thank you, thank you.

00:02:31.900 --> 00:02:34.630
So, some of you are publishers here today
and you're trying to figure out,

00:02:34.640 --> 00:02:38.030
well, how is this digital book revolution
going to change your industry

00:02:38.150 --> 00:02:39.310
and how do you get into that?

00:02:39.400 --> 00:02:40.800
And we'll show you.

00:02:41.050 --> 00:02:46.570
And some of you are web developers that
want to learn how to take your skills,

00:02:46.830 --> 00:02:49.000
which are completely
valid in this new world,

00:02:49.290 --> 00:02:54.340
and how do you take a piece of this
gigantic monetary action that's

00:02:54.340 --> 00:02:56.800
growing at a tremendous pace.

00:02:56.960 --> 00:03:00.650
And we'll show you how to make
your books better than the rest.

00:03:00.800 --> 00:03:03.790
You've seen books that look like this.

00:03:04.190 --> 00:03:08.980
These are text-centric books
that flow from page to page.

00:03:08.980 --> 00:03:12.460
We're going to show you how to
take text-centric books and make

00:03:12.460 --> 00:03:16.160
them look beautiful on the iPad,
the iPhone and the iPod

00:03:16.160 --> 00:03:17.730
Touch inside of iBooks.

00:03:17.860 --> 00:03:21.380
We're going to show you how to
add style and visual treatment,

00:03:21.450 --> 00:03:26.220
how to add audio and video and fonts
to give your text some character.

00:03:26.270 --> 00:03:29.110
We'll show you some new
features around this as well.

00:03:29.300 --> 00:03:35.520
But did you know that digital
books can also look like this?

00:03:36.380 --> 00:03:38.500
Or like this.

00:03:38.550 --> 00:03:42.890
These are called fixed layout
books and are new to iBooks.

00:03:43.340 --> 00:03:47.210
With fixed layout books you
can bleed from edge to edge.

00:03:47.210 --> 00:03:50.200
All the things that used to
be only available in high

00:03:50.200 --> 00:03:54.520
quality color printing presses,
you can now do inside of digital books.

00:03:54.610 --> 00:03:57.040
And we're going to show
you how again today.

00:03:57.080 --> 00:04:01.090
And we'll show you how to go beyond
just what you can do with print

00:04:01.130 --> 00:04:03.390
and make your books come alive.

00:04:06.390 --> 00:04:11.860
So the first question I want to
answer for you is why make a book?

00:04:12.550 --> 00:04:15.500
And the answer I have for you is content.

00:04:15.550 --> 00:04:18.180
You want to focus on content
when you're creating a book,

00:04:18.210 --> 00:04:19.660
not code.

00:04:19.700 --> 00:04:25.170
And with iBooks, you have all kinds of
beautiful stylizing options.

00:04:25.890 --> 00:04:30.360
Books are based on standard technologies.

00:04:30.360 --> 00:04:31.400
So what does that mean for you?

00:04:31.520 --> 00:04:33.770
Well, one, they're easy to create.

00:04:33.960 --> 00:04:36.350
There are lots of tools available.

00:04:37.300 --> 00:04:40.160
And they're based on top of WebKit.

00:04:40.160 --> 00:04:43.180
So all of the techniques that
you've learned this week with

00:04:43.180 --> 00:04:46.860
WebKit can be taken over to books.

00:04:48.450 --> 00:04:52.880
And because this is based on standards,
your books when authored once for iBooks

00:04:53.100 --> 00:04:56.380
will also work in several other readers.

00:04:57.740 --> 00:04:59.360
Anyone can publish a book.

00:04:59.510 --> 00:05:04.510
There are, like I said,
many tools available, but none required.

00:05:05.720 --> 00:05:08.640
And finally,
one advantage of making a book over, say,

00:05:08.710 --> 00:05:12.600
a website, is that books can
travel with your reader.

00:05:12.750 --> 00:05:16.990
They take it with them in their pocket,
on their iPad, on their phones,

00:05:16.990 --> 00:05:19.760
and they can pick up anywhere they want.

00:05:19.920 --> 00:05:23.430
They can be on a bus, in a car,
hopefully not driving,

00:05:23.490 --> 00:05:27.800
and they don't need an internet
connection unlike a website.

00:05:28.480 --> 00:05:30.960
So let's talk about iBooks.

00:05:30.970 --> 00:05:34.000
Most of you probably know
iBooks is Apple's reader app.

00:05:34.080 --> 00:05:37.880
And it's the most fully featured
digital book reader on the market.

00:05:38.070 --> 00:05:42.240
It allows you to have visually rich
images and layout like the books

00:05:42.240 --> 00:05:44.490
that I just showed you images of.

00:05:44.590 --> 00:05:49.200
We of course give you the ability to
add audio and video to your books.

00:05:49.290 --> 00:05:53.760
And with iBooks, the store is just on the
backside of the bookshelf.

00:05:53.820 --> 00:05:56.770
Your reader doesn't even have
to leave the app in order to

00:05:56.770 --> 00:05:58.610
go buy your next best seller.

00:05:58.730 --> 00:06:00.900
So we'll teach you a few things today.

00:06:00.970 --> 00:06:04.520
Number one, how to build an EPUB.

00:06:04.570 --> 00:06:09.800
EPUB is the standard
building block of books.

00:06:10.020 --> 00:06:13.970
Number two, we'll talk about how
to build flowing books.

00:06:14.090 --> 00:06:17.430
And flowing books are the text-centric
books that I talked about earlier.

00:06:17.650 --> 00:06:22.550
We'll give you techniques for
taking HTML and CSS and make

00:06:22.630 --> 00:06:24.840
them beautiful inside of iBooks.

00:06:24.880 --> 00:06:28.920
We'll show you how to enhance your
books with audio and video and also

00:06:29.060 --> 00:06:33.160
how to include fonts so that you
can give your text some character.

00:06:33.380 --> 00:06:36.820
And we'll show you a feature
called non-linear documents.

00:06:36.820 --> 00:06:41.860
Non-linear documents allow your readers
to break out of the linearity of a

00:06:42.300 --> 00:06:47.260
book and give them content that's
usually relegated to the appendix.

00:06:47.390 --> 00:06:49.680
We'll show you how to
embed those in the book,

00:06:49.680 --> 00:06:53.330
give your users a way to get to that
content and then quickly get back to

00:06:53.330 --> 00:06:55.760
where they were in their reading order.

00:06:56.170 --> 00:06:59.540
Finally, we'll show you how to
make a fixed layout book.

00:06:59.570 --> 00:07:02.200
The fixed layout book are
the picture-heavy books

00:07:02.200 --> 00:07:03.600
that I showed you earlier.

00:07:03.640 --> 00:07:06.850
We'll show you how to use
CSS to precisely place

00:07:06.850 --> 00:07:08.540
your elements on the page.

00:07:08.570 --> 00:07:14.400
And we'll show you how to go
far beyond the print experience.

00:07:14.940 --> 00:07:17.290
To talk about EPUB,
I want to introduce you

00:07:17.370 --> 00:07:19.670
Casey Dougherty from the iBookstore.

00:07:22.540 --> 00:07:22.540
Thanks, Al.

00:07:26.320 --> 00:07:27.240
A little water to get me going.

00:07:27.310 --> 00:07:28.800
Hey everyone, I'm Casey.

00:07:28.800 --> 00:07:30.480
I'm on the iBookstore team.

00:07:30.580 --> 00:07:34.540
And today I'm going to teach you
how you can make books for iBooks.

00:07:34.600 --> 00:07:38.540
Now, as Al said,
EPUB is the building block for iBooks.

00:07:38.540 --> 00:07:43.960
So to teach you how to make a book,
I'm going to start by teaching you EPUB.

00:07:45.370 --> 00:07:47.460
I'll show you the contents of EPUB.

00:07:47.510 --> 00:07:50.360
I'll also show you how you can
define a reading order and a

00:07:50.410 --> 00:07:52.460
table of contents for your EPUB.

00:07:52.590 --> 00:07:55.350
And then finally,
we'll look at how you can

00:07:55.350 --> 00:07:57.710
customize the iBooks experience.

00:07:58.170 --> 00:08:01.300
An EPUB is web technology.

00:08:01.370 --> 00:08:07.430
In an EPUB you'll see HTML, CSS,
XHTML and XML.

00:08:07.720 --> 00:08:11.980
In fact, you can think of an EPUB as a
website that has been bundled

00:08:12.070 --> 00:08:16.910
together for distribution and
given the extension of .epub.

00:08:17.180 --> 00:08:20.000
In fact,
if you look at an EPUB's file structure,

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:22.860
it looks very much like a website.

00:08:23.040 --> 00:08:28.200
Inside the EPUB is an OEBPS folder
and a meta-INF folder.

00:08:28.320 --> 00:08:32.830
The OEBPS folder is the open ebook
packaging structure and it contains

00:08:33.370 --> 00:08:35.940
all of the content of your book.

00:08:36.050 --> 00:08:40.350
In this case, we're seeing web content,
that's XHTML and CSS,

00:08:40.450 --> 00:08:44.400
that's the content of your book
and the style for your book.

00:08:44.520 --> 00:08:51.800
There's also a lot of media,
including images, video, audio and fonts.

00:08:51.920 --> 00:08:55.500
And then in addition to this
standard web content is also

00:08:55.740 --> 00:08:59.230
three EPUB specific XML files.

00:08:59.370 --> 00:09:02.430
This is the OPF file,
the NCX file and the

00:09:02.780 --> 00:09:07.860
Apple Display Options file,
which we've abbreviated as ADO here.

00:09:08.030 --> 00:09:13.440
Now the OPF and the NCX file are
crucial to your EPUB structure.

00:09:13.440 --> 00:09:16.870
So I'm going to start
by teaching you those.

00:09:17.700 --> 00:09:22.960
The OPF file is the open packaging
format file for your book and in it

00:09:22.960 --> 00:09:27.280
contains the metadata for your book,
this is all the information

00:09:27.280 --> 00:09:31.320
about your book,
a manifest that lists all of the

00:09:31.320 --> 00:09:33.910
files that make up your book,

00:09:34.090 --> 00:09:38.840
A spine, which defines the reading
linear order of your book.

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:43.040
And also the guide, which identifies the
key files of your book.

00:09:43.040 --> 00:09:46.030
This is the key structure.

00:09:46.270 --> 00:09:49.320
Now,
metadata may not sound like much fun,

00:09:49.340 --> 00:09:52.840
but it's crucial in defining
how your book looks on the

00:09:52.840 --> 00:09:55.480
iTunes and iBooks bookshelf.

00:09:55.610 --> 00:09:58.320
In this example of Harry and Horsey,
you'll see that we have

00:09:58.320 --> 00:09:59.500
a cover for your book.

00:09:59.560 --> 00:10:03.140
There's also the title and
there's the author of the book.

00:10:03.190 --> 00:10:07.090
And EPUB actually requires
you to include three pieces of

00:10:07.090 --> 00:10:09.670
information in your book's metadata.

00:10:10.070 --> 00:10:12.310
And that's the title,

00:10:12.460 --> 00:10:16.760
A unique identifier for your book,
which is usually the ISBN number,

00:10:16.840 --> 00:10:20.340
and also the language,
in this case it's English.

00:10:20.470 --> 00:10:24.940
In addition to this required metadata,
I have also included the subject,

00:10:25.030 --> 00:10:29.610
which is the genre of the book,
the creator, which is the author,

00:10:29.680 --> 00:10:33.770
and I've included a meta tag that
defines the cover image for your book.

00:10:33.850 --> 00:10:38.380
And all of this metadata works
together to define how your book

00:10:38.380 --> 00:10:40.940
looks on the iBooks bookshelf.

00:10:41.350 --> 00:10:45.360
In addition to the metadata in the OPF,
there's also the manifest.

00:10:45.410 --> 00:10:49.200
The manifest lists all of the
documents that make up your book.

00:10:49.200 --> 00:10:53.040
So that's your NCX file,
your content documents,

00:10:53.070 --> 00:10:57.140
all of your XHTML,
your images and your CSS styling,

00:10:57.360 --> 00:11:01.160
everything that makes up
your book is listed there.

00:11:01.890 --> 00:11:04.690
In addition to the manifest,
there's also the spine of your book.

00:11:04.830 --> 00:11:10.100
Now the spine of an EPUB works very
much like the spine of a physical

00:11:10.160 --> 00:11:15.620
book in that it binds together your
chapters into a linear reading order.

00:11:15.730 --> 00:11:19.630
So for this example,
we actually have page one, page two,

00:11:19.740 --> 00:11:23.210
page three and page four,
and we've made each of them

00:11:23.210 --> 00:11:24.950
a separate XHTML document.

00:11:25.170 --> 00:11:31.810
The spine only references XHTML documents
because those are your content documents.

00:11:32.280 --> 00:11:35.280
The metadata,
the manifest and the spine are all

00:11:35.530 --> 00:11:38.900
required attributes of the OPF file.

00:11:39.250 --> 00:11:42.840
The guide is optional,
but it's good practice.

00:11:42.900 --> 00:11:48.120
Because the guide identifies
key files within your book.

00:11:48.170 --> 00:11:52.540
In the example here,
you'll see that we've identified both the

00:11:52.540 --> 00:11:55.710
cover and there's also the type of text.

00:11:55.870 --> 00:12:00.200
So no matter what our
XHTML files might be named,

00:12:00.250 --> 00:12:05.040
we can tell iBooks, hey,
cover.XHTML is the cover page of my book.

00:12:05.060 --> 00:12:10.630
And page1.XHTML is the start
of the main text of my book.

00:12:10.720 --> 00:12:15.430
So type of text communicates
this is the start of the content.

00:12:15.480 --> 00:12:17.280
It's probably equivalent to chapter one.

00:12:17.280 --> 00:12:21.940
And it means that anything
before that was front matter,

00:12:22.070 --> 00:12:24.390
like a cover or a copyright.

00:12:24.870 --> 00:12:26.040
So that's the OPF.

00:12:26.040 --> 00:12:29.400
Remember, metadata,
manifest and spine are all required.

00:12:29.420 --> 00:12:32.740
The guide is optional but good practice.

00:12:32.790 --> 00:12:36.540
Next, I want to show you the NCX file.

00:12:36.540 --> 00:12:41.380
NCX is the Navigation
Control XML and that's just fancy

00:12:41.380 --> 00:12:43.620
talk for a table of contents.

00:12:43.630 --> 00:12:46.140
This is a table of contents in iBooks.

00:12:46.150 --> 00:12:49.600
You can see that there's a
listing of the different entries

00:12:49.600 --> 00:12:51.080
in the table of contents.

00:12:51.080 --> 00:12:54.750
And iBooks has actually assigned
each of them a page number.

00:12:54.800 --> 00:12:58.100
That page number is a dynamic number.

00:12:58.100 --> 00:13:01.870
iBooks is able to construct
this table of contents based

00:13:01.870 --> 00:13:06.220
off of a NavMap XML structure.

00:13:06.230 --> 00:13:11.240
In that NavMap, you'll see that there's
a series of nav points.

00:13:11.240 --> 00:13:14.850
Each of those nav points has a
defined play order and that play

00:13:14.850 --> 00:13:20.670
order defines the ordering of that nav
point in the books table of contents.

00:13:20.930 --> 00:13:25.060
Within each nav point is a nav label.

00:13:25.090 --> 00:13:29.600
That's the text that's forward
facing and is what the reader

00:13:29.600 --> 00:13:31.500
sees in the table of contents.

00:13:31.530 --> 00:13:33.250
And there's also a content source.

00:13:33.320 --> 00:13:37.730
That's the URL of where the reader
will be taken when they select

00:13:38.360 --> 00:13:40.860
that item in the table of contents.

00:13:41.290 --> 00:13:45.080
For this example, for this nav map,
iBooks will create a table of

00:13:45.080 --> 00:13:47.790
contents that looks like this.

00:13:48.820 --> 00:13:50.500
You'll see that there's
two entries in there,

00:13:50.580 --> 00:13:54.490
our title page and chapter,
and each of them have

00:13:54.490 --> 00:13:57.210
an assigned page number.

00:13:58.360 --> 00:14:00.330
So that's the OPF in the NCX.

00:14:00.460 --> 00:14:04.420
There's a third XML file that
I want to talk to you about today,

00:14:04.450 --> 00:14:06.230
and that's the
Apple Display Options file.

00:14:06.300 --> 00:14:10.260
The ADO file lives in the MetaINF folder.

00:14:10.260 --> 00:14:17.190
It gives you, the developer,
four customization methods,

00:14:17.190 --> 00:14:22.510
including fixed layout, zoom level,
fonts and orientation lock.

00:14:23.440 --> 00:14:27.440
And each of these options can be
defined either globally for all

00:14:27.630 --> 00:14:32.000
of the devices of iBooks or can be
defined on a device-specific level.

00:14:32.100 --> 00:14:36.120
So let me show you the code to do that.

00:14:36.870 --> 00:14:40.600
In the Apple Display Options file,
you'll see that there's a platform name.

00:14:40.710 --> 00:14:44.190
If you wanted to find this globally,
you'll want to give it

00:14:44.400 --> 00:14:45.880
a name of an asterisk.

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:50.520
This will apply it to the iPad,
the iPhone and the iPod Touch.

00:14:50.700 --> 00:14:54.350
However, there might be a time where you
want one of those options to apply

00:14:54.520 --> 00:14:56.560
to just a specific type of device.

00:14:56.560 --> 00:15:01.540
So we also give you the ability
to define it just for the iPad.

00:15:01.600 --> 00:15:05.990
Or you could set the value to iPhone,
which applies it to both

00:15:05.990 --> 00:15:08.950
the iPhone and the iPod.

00:15:09.050 --> 00:15:12.440
Next, I want to walk you through
each of the display options.

00:15:12.600 --> 00:15:15.020
First is Fixed Layout.

00:15:15.070 --> 00:15:18.520
Fixed Layout is that highly designed
book that Al was showing you,

00:15:18.520 --> 00:15:22.060
and he's going to tell you how to make
one of those in just a few minutes.

00:15:22.220 --> 00:15:25.290
Second is Open to Spread.

00:15:25.390 --> 00:15:29.120
You can think of Open to Spread as
like a zoom level for your book.

00:15:29.210 --> 00:15:32.640
So if you have a book where
you want the reader's first

00:15:32.720 --> 00:15:36.770
experience to be a two-page spread,
you'll want to set the

00:15:36.810 --> 00:15:39.320
Open to Spread to True.

00:15:40.120 --> 00:15:42.820
Third, specified fonts.

00:15:43.350 --> 00:15:46.890
If the fonts in your book are
critical to the book's experience,

00:15:46.960 --> 00:15:50.760
then you should include the
Apple Display Option file of

00:15:50.760 --> 00:15:53.110
specified fonts and set it to true.

00:15:53.520 --> 00:15:56.100
And finally is Orientation Lock.

00:15:56.210 --> 00:16:01.900
iBooks displays your book great
in both portrait and in landscape,

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:05.400
but there might be a time where
you have text that goes sideways

00:16:05.400 --> 00:16:09.210
or topsy-turvy on your book,
and that would make the reader

00:16:09.400 --> 00:16:12.280
want to rotate the device in
order to read that text better.

00:16:12.420 --> 00:16:15.980
So if you have a book like that,
you will want to set the

00:16:15.980 --> 00:16:20.530
Orientation Lock to either
landscape only or portrait only.

00:16:20.950 --> 00:16:22.960
and that's Apple Display Options.

00:16:22.960 --> 00:16:25.920
It's a really great way of
augmenting the reading experience,

00:16:25.920 --> 00:16:29.940
but it's only a small part
of the total EPUB package.

00:16:29.970 --> 00:16:34.060
All good books need a great design.

00:16:34.060 --> 00:16:38.640
And so I'm going to show you a way
today to design great flowing books.

00:16:38.640 --> 00:16:42.210
And Al is going to tell you how
to design great fixed books.

00:16:42.420 --> 00:16:45.400
First,
I want to tell you about flowing books.

00:16:45.480 --> 00:16:50.490
You'll want to make a flowing book if
you have a text heavy book like a novel,

00:16:50.530 --> 00:16:54.810
because flowing books give
the user control over both the

00:16:54.990 --> 00:16:57.560
font face and the font size.

00:16:57.570 --> 00:17:01.200
As I told you earlier,
a book is really just a web page.

00:17:01.230 --> 00:17:04.600
So this is how a book looks in Safari.

00:17:04.870 --> 00:17:08.560
iBooks takes this long scrolling
document and neatly divides

00:17:08.560 --> 00:17:10.560
it into individual pages.

00:17:11.390 --> 00:17:14.970
Now this helps your content
look more like a book,

00:17:14.970 --> 00:17:19.140
but it's still missing that
quality design of a novel.

00:17:19.230 --> 00:17:22.770
So today I'm going to give you
some code and show you how you can

00:17:22.770 --> 00:17:28.640
easily turn this plain Jane book
into a great design novel.

00:17:28.700 --> 00:17:31.760
I'm going to show you how
to create stunning text,

00:17:31.820 --> 00:17:35.720
how you can embed fonts in your book,
how you can incorporate

00:17:35.840 --> 00:17:40.760
auxiliary content in your book
using an EPUB specific feature,

00:17:40.790 --> 00:17:45.360
and finally how you can enhance
your books with audio and video.

00:17:46.720 --> 00:17:52.950
The two most important things
that you can do when creating

00:17:52.990 --> 00:17:56.290
a flowing book is one,

00:17:56.500 --> 00:18:00.200
Define your width and percentage,
not pixels.

00:18:00.300 --> 00:18:04.460
And two, define your font size in ems.

00:18:04.650 --> 00:18:09.660
These two rules will ensure
that your book flows and adapts

00:18:09.810 --> 00:18:14.890
so that it works well on any
size device in any orientation.

00:18:15.110 --> 00:18:17.200
The example here is of a block quote.

00:18:17.270 --> 00:18:20.540
This is a very typical example
of a block quote in an eBook.

00:18:20.680 --> 00:18:25.340
You can see that the block quote
isn't taking use of its full page

00:18:25.350 --> 00:18:28.690
real estate there and it's off center.

00:18:28.950 --> 00:18:33.030
But even worse is if you rotate
the device and look at this in a

00:18:33.040 --> 00:18:38.140
smaller viewport or a smaller page,
this block quote now is even,

00:18:38.160 --> 00:18:40.470
it's shoved off the edge of the book.

00:18:40.670 --> 00:18:42.800
There's actually text
being clipped on the edge.

00:18:42.820 --> 00:18:49.680
And that's because this block quote
was defined precisely using pixels.

00:18:49.810 --> 00:18:56.800
It has a set width of 350 pixels and
it has a left margin of 50 pixels.

00:18:57.290 --> 00:18:59.040
Fortunately,
this is really easy to fix if

00:18:59.040 --> 00:19:00.800
you just follow our two rules.

00:19:00.800 --> 00:19:05.490
So change the font size to 1M,
change the width to 90% and give it

00:19:05.490 --> 00:19:07.690
a left and a right margin of auto.

00:19:07.800 --> 00:19:09.620
The result's much better.

00:19:09.820 --> 00:19:13.490
Now you have a block quote that's
taking full use of the page real

00:19:14.160 --> 00:19:15.800
estate and it stays centered.

00:19:15.800 --> 00:19:20.710
And that's because by defining a width
of 90%, you ensure that the width of

00:19:20.710 --> 00:19:25.800
your paragraph is 90% of the page width
no matter what the size of device.

00:19:25.800 --> 00:19:27.030
Thanks.

00:19:27.940 --> 00:19:32.610
Okay, so with those two simple rules,
we have a great structure for our book.

00:19:32.870 --> 00:19:34.740
Next,
let's have some fun and add a bit of

00:19:34.740 --> 00:19:37.560
design and color and embellishments.

00:19:38.800 --> 00:19:43.250
Styling books is actually quite
simple because they're made up of a

00:19:43.420 --> 00:19:45.300
bundle of nearly identical content.

00:19:45.300 --> 00:19:49.070
That's because books are made of
chapters and generally you want every

00:19:49.070 --> 00:19:52.300
chapter to have about the same design.

00:19:52.300 --> 00:19:58.610
And you can easily add that design
without having to add a lot of extra

00:19:58.610 --> 00:20:03.890
HTML markup because you can use
CSS pseudo classes and pseudo elements

00:20:04.210 --> 00:20:09.830
to select just the text that you
want to add the style to dynamically.

00:20:09.900 --> 00:20:13.970
You may already know of the
CSS pseudo classes Active and Hover.

00:20:14.030 --> 00:20:17.150
Today, I'm going to tell you
about the pseudo class,

00:20:17.180 --> 00:20:20.350
First of Type,
and then we'll look at pseudo elements,

00:20:20.350 --> 00:20:24.400
First Line, First Letter and Before.

00:20:24.480 --> 00:20:27.270
First, I want to show you First of Type.

00:20:28.270 --> 00:20:30.870
Oh, and that's our Plain Jane book
and we're turning it in as a

00:20:30.870 --> 00:20:32.850
reminder to this nice novel.

00:20:33.190 --> 00:20:35.430
So, first of type.

00:20:36.570 --> 00:20:40.820
For each of these examples,
we're going to reference a chapter class.

00:20:40.820 --> 00:20:45.010
And you can think of this as a
container div for your entire chapter.

00:20:45.120 --> 00:20:48.440
And for first of type,
we're going to use it to accomplish

00:20:48.570 --> 00:20:52.430
a very common design of a novel,
where you want the text at the

00:20:52.530 --> 00:20:55.780
start of a chapter to start
down a little bit on the page.

00:20:55.900 --> 00:21:00.140
So in the chapter class,
you want to identify the first paragraph

00:21:00.250 --> 00:21:05.510
within that class and give it a margin,
a top margin of 20%.

00:21:07.110 --> 00:21:12.520
First of Type and top margin of 20%
is added just to that first paragraph.

00:21:12.740 --> 00:21:16.400
None of the other paragraphs
within that chapter are affected.

00:21:17.270 --> 00:21:22.400
Another really good way of adding
great style to your books is to

00:21:22.470 --> 00:21:24.080
create a drop cap for your books.

00:21:24.080 --> 00:21:28.240
So a drop cap is when you bump
up the font size on just that

00:21:28.500 --> 00:21:30.520
first letter of a chapter.

00:21:30.580 --> 00:21:34.200
So today we're going to
accomplish just that by using

00:21:34.200 --> 00:21:36.790
the pseudo element first letter.

00:21:37.070 --> 00:21:41.110
So just as in our previous example,
you're going to go

00:21:41.140 --> 00:21:44.140
into the chapter class,
identify the first

00:21:44.180 --> 00:21:46.040
paragraph of that class.

00:21:46.100 --> 00:21:48.810
And then this time we're going
to drill a little deeper and

00:21:48.810 --> 00:21:51.560
select just that first letter.

00:21:51.650 --> 00:21:54.100
We're going to bump up
the font size to 6M,

00:21:54.160 --> 00:21:57.160
add a color of red and
add a float of left.

00:21:57.360 --> 00:22:01.440
And that float is what makes it so
that your paragraph text actually

00:22:01.720 --> 00:22:05.430
floats around the enlarged initial.

00:22:05.520 --> 00:22:08.700
And with that bit of code,
we have a great looking

00:22:08.820 --> 00:22:10.410
drop cap in our book.

00:22:11.620 --> 00:22:15.910
Another really common design
element that I see in both physical

00:22:15.910 --> 00:22:22.640
and in eBooks is to bold just the
first line of that first paragraph.

00:22:22.690 --> 00:22:26.930
Now usually when I see this in an eBook,
it's been hard coded into the

00:22:26.960 --> 00:22:31.600
HTML and this means that there
might be 10 words that are bolded,

00:22:31.650 --> 00:22:34.410
but however many it is,
it's always the same number

00:22:34.410 --> 00:22:38.000
no matter what my device size,
no matter what my font size.

00:22:38.050 --> 00:22:43.270
And that means that it's pretty much
never just the first line that's bolded.

00:22:43.470 --> 00:22:48.640
This is really easy to fix using
the pseudo-element first line.

00:22:49.730 --> 00:22:52.970
So just as before,
you're going to go into your chapter

00:22:52.970 --> 00:22:55.880
class and then you're going to
identify the first paragraph and

00:22:55.880 --> 00:22:59.470
then you're going to stylize just the
first line of that first paragraph

00:22:59.680 --> 00:23:02.640
and giving it a font weight of bold.

00:23:02.650 --> 00:23:06.040
And while it's just a minor
adjustment in this keynote,

00:23:06.100 --> 00:23:09.700
let me tell you,
it makes a big difference in a book.

00:23:09.730 --> 00:23:14.280
So, so far I've shown you how you can use
pseudo classes and pseudo elements

00:23:14.280 --> 00:23:16.640
to actually stylize your content.

00:23:16.700 --> 00:23:20.450
Next, I want to show you how you can
use a pseudo element to actually

00:23:20.450 --> 00:23:22.840
insert content into your book.

00:23:22.870 --> 00:23:26.880
And this is accomplished using
the CSS content declaration.

00:23:26.930 --> 00:23:31.360
Content can be used with either the
pseudo elements before or after,

00:23:31.360 --> 00:23:35.440
and you can use it to insert text,
images, or in this case,

00:23:35.450 --> 00:23:38.800
we're going to use the
Unicode character for a star.

00:23:38.830 --> 00:23:42.940
And we're using it to add an
embellishment into our book.

00:23:42.960 --> 00:23:45.380
So for this example,
we're adding the Unicode

00:23:45.460 --> 00:23:48.440
character of a star,
making it red and giving

00:23:48.440 --> 00:23:49.540
a font size of 2M.

00:23:49.540 --> 00:23:52.240
We want the star to be
a little bit bigger.

00:23:52.250 --> 00:23:55.590
And because our chapter header up
there is still looking pretty plain,

00:23:55.740 --> 00:23:58.300
let's go in and stylize our H1 header.

00:23:58.440 --> 00:23:59.270
We're going to make it red.

00:23:59.390 --> 00:24:00.860
We're on the iPad after all.

00:24:00.860 --> 00:24:02.570
You should use some color.

00:24:02.690 --> 00:24:07.060
And we're going to increase the
font size to 3M and set a text

00:24:07.060 --> 00:24:09.440
transform to make it all uppercase.

00:24:09.450 --> 00:24:14.740
And with that little bit of code,
we have our final great novel design.

00:24:14.780 --> 00:24:16.280
So another really great way to do this
is to use the Unicode text transform.

00:24:16.480 --> 00:24:18.880
And it's a really great way
of adding style and adding

00:24:18.880 --> 00:24:20.570
character to your books as fonts.

