But what they forgot is that
sometimes layout is important.

00:31:53.800 --> 00:31:55.640
Sometimes layout is crucial to your book.

00:31:55.800 --> 00:31:58.650
So we had a little
innovation back last year,

00:31:59.050 --> 00:32:01.510
late last year,
and we added something called

00:32:01.580 --> 00:32:02.800
fixed layout to iBooks.

00:32:02.800 --> 00:32:05.800
And fixed layout is a standard EPUB.

00:32:05.800 --> 00:32:08.920
It's the same EPUB that
Casey just taught you how to make,

00:32:08.920 --> 00:32:11.800
but we've added a few things
to respect your layouts.

00:32:11.800 --> 00:32:14.600
So let's look at that.

00:32:16.140 --> 00:32:17.660
Once again, fixed layouts.

00:32:17.730 --> 00:32:21.260
We respect your precise
layouts as a publisher.

00:32:21.320 --> 00:32:25.310
You can place your elements
anywhere you want on the page.

00:32:25.420 --> 00:32:26.940
You can bleed them edge to edge.

00:32:27.100 --> 00:32:32.100
And you can even place them on top of
each other and have text over images.

00:32:32.320 --> 00:32:35.930
The example you see here is from
a book called "Five Good Reasons

00:32:35.930 --> 00:32:38.090
to Punch a Dolphin in the Mouth."

00:32:39.020 --> 00:32:44.340
So anyway, as you can see with this book,
the positioning of the

00:32:44.340 --> 00:32:46.260
elements is crucial.

00:32:47.770 --> 00:32:49.300
So we'll show you a few things today.

00:32:49.420 --> 00:32:52.300
One, how to set up your book.

00:32:52.420 --> 00:32:55.820
Two, how to lay out the
elements on your pages.

00:32:55.950 --> 00:33:01.620
Three, how to prepare your images
that go in your EPUB bundle.

00:33:01.690 --> 00:33:06.570
And four, how to enhance your books
so that they come alive.

00:33:09.440 --> 00:33:16.300
As I mentioned, fixed books are the same
EPUB format as flowing books.

00:33:16.560 --> 00:33:19.500
There are three additions
that you need to respect.

00:33:19.750 --> 00:33:21.300
One.

00:33:21.950 --> 00:33:26.500
You need one XHTML document
per page in your book.

00:33:26.630 --> 00:33:32.000
Two, you must specify the viewport
dimensions for each page.

00:33:32.050 --> 00:33:35.180
And three,
you need to set the Apple display

00:33:35.180 --> 00:33:37.590
option of fixed layout to true.

00:33:37.760 --> 00:33:42.100
Now let's go through each of
these last three points in detail.

00:33:42.220 --> 00:33:45.580
Here's an example of a
book called Pete the Cat.

00:33:45.880 --> 00:33:47.400
As you can see, it's beautiful.

00:33:47.490 --> 00:33:51.950
The images spread across the middle.

00:33:52.110 --> 00:33:56.010
This is actually two different pages.

00:33:56.450 --> 00:33:59.580
Two different XHTML documents.

00:33:59.760 --> 00:34:01.600
You can point to the same image.

00:34:01.680 --> 00:34:04.700
There are reasons why you may want to
do that and reasons why you may not.

00:34:04.770 --> 00:34:06.800
We'll talk about images in a moment.

00:34:06.880 --> 00:34:10.090
The takeaway here, that's two pages.

00:34:11.350 --> 00:34:16.760
Second, you need to specify the viewport
dimensions for your book.

00:34:16.760 --> 00:34:21.780
Your users are able to zoom in and
out of the content on the page.

00:34:21.780 --> 00:34:26.930
Not only that,
but your book might be viewed on an iPad,

00:34:26.940 --> 00:34:31.900
it might be viewed on an
iPhone or an iPod Touch,

00:34:31.900 --> 00:34:31.900
so the screen size changes.

00:34:32.270 --> 00:34:36.700
The viewport allows iBooks to know
what the aspect ratio of the pages

00:34:36.700 --> 00:34:39.490
are that you intend for your pages.

00:34:40.270 --> 00:34:43.300
Your viewport dimensions should
correspond to your body dimensions.

00:34:43.300 --> 00:34:46.790
And we'll talk about the CSS in a moment,
but keep that in mind.

00:34:47.110 --> 00:34:50.040
And you must specify your
viewport dimensions in every

00:34:50.040 --> 00:34:52.240
content document in your book.

00:34:52.330 --> 00:34:55.940
Here's an example of the code.

00:34:56.360 --> 00:34:58.140
To set your viewport.

00:34:58.250 --> 00:35:00.190
This is the head of your HTML.

00:35:00.330 --> 00:35:02.420
It includes things like the title.

00:35:02.420 --> 00:35:04.490
It also includes the
last element in here,

00:35:05.390 --> 00:35:10.160
which is a meta tag called
viewport with a content set with a

00:35:10.460 --> 00:35:13.300
width of 800 and a height of 600.

00:35:13.450 --> 00:35:16.200
Remember those numbers,
we're going to come back to them.

00:35:16.850 --> 00:35:19.750
The last thing you need to do so
that your book will be recognized

00:35:19.750 --> 00:35:23.580
as a fixed layout book is to set
the fixed layout option to true

00:35:23.900 --> 00:35:25.500
in your Apple Display options.

00:35:25.560 --> 00:35:29.780
That's the key so that iBooks needs
to know how to open your book.

00:35:29.830 --> 00:35:33.810
And remember, as Casey mentioned,
you can specify the platform

00:35:33.880 --> 00:35:36.590
name to iPad or iPhone,
or iPhone is both.

00:35:36.820 --> 00:35:40.460
In this case, we specified Star,
which means we want it to be fixed

00:35:40.690 --> 00:35:43.770
layout on all three platforms,
all three devices.

00:35:44.900 --> 00:35:48.120
All right, now let's look at how
to layout your pages.

00:35:48.310 --> 00:35:52.220
I mentioned setting viewport dimensions,
but you also,

00:35:52.260 --> 00:35:56.950
in order to get absolute positioning,
you need to specify your

00:35:56.950 --> 00:35:59.460
body dimensions for your CSS.

00:35:59.460 --> 00:36:02.900
We recommend that you match them
to your viewport dimensions.

00:36:02.950 --> 00:36:05.240
Once you've specified
your body dimensions,

00:36:05.270 --> 00:36:08.900
you can then work in pixel and
position elements anywhere you want.

00:36:09.110 --> 00:36:11.900
You can use absolute or
relative positioning.

00:36:11.900 --> 00:36:16.520
Relative positioning allows you to
move your elements based on where they

00:36:16.520 --> 00:36:18.900
would be from their default position.

00:36:18.900 --> 00:36:24.190
And absolute positioning allows
you to specify element position

00:36:24.190 --> 00:36:29.250
with respect to the container
in which those elements live.

00:36:31.150 --> 00:36:33.360
So let's take an example.

00:36:33.360 --> 00:36:38.470
This is a page from a
beautiful fixed layout book.

00:36:38.630 --> 00:36:43.120
As you can see it has a full background
image and it has some text that's

00:36:43.130 --> 00:36:45.440
slightly tilted in the top left corner.

00:36:45.550 --> 00:36:47.790
Let's break this down
and see how it's built.

00:36:48.090 --> 00:36:50.260
First, the HTML.

00:36:50.890 --> 00:36:51.900
Here it is.

00:36:51.980 --> 00:36:52.960
Pretty simple.

00:36:53.010 --> 00:36:55.840
Our body has one div.

00:36:55.930 --> 00:36:57.540
Its class is page 4.

00:36:57.930 --> 00:37:03.200
Inside that there's an image element
and there are four lines of text.

00:37:03.270 --> 00:37:07.610
All the text is wrapped in a paragraph
tag and then the second and third line

00:37:07.610 --> 00:37:10.040
are wrapped in a span with a class of P2.

00:37:10.040 --> 00:37:13.920
The fourth line is wrapped
in a span with a class of P3.

00:37:14.010 --> 00:37:15.900
That's the HTML required
to make this page.

00:37:15.900 --> 00:37:17.080
Simple.

00:37:17.120 --> 00:37:22.220
Let's look at the CSS that's
required to position these elements.

00:37:23.340 --> 00:37:27.180
So,
our body has a width and height of 800.

00:37:27.190 --> 00:37:29.860
As I mentioned before,
this should match your

00:37:29.860 --> 00:37:31.300
viewport dimensions.

00:37:31.340 --> 00:37:36.540
What we've added here is a border,
a thin solid yellow line.

00:37:36.560 --> 00:37:40.690
Now that's for you, the developer,
so that you can tell what your borders

00:37:40.760 --> 00:37:42.940
are as you're positioning your elements.

00:37:42.960 --> 00:37:46.910
Don't forget, if you use this technique,
remove it before you ship or else all

00:37:46.910 --> 00:37:49.260
your pages will have thin yellow borders.

00:37:49.270 --> 00:37:52.020
And we've specified a margin of zero.

00:37:52.020 --> 00:37:55.030
I told you that iBooks is
based on WebKit and it is.

00:37:55.120 --> 00:37:56.560
This is a web view.

00:37:56.610 --> 00:38:01.120
By setting a margin to zero,
you can go edge to edge.

00:38:02.010 --> 00:38:03.620
Next, the CSS for the image.

00:38:03.700 --> 00:38:09.740
We've specified a position of absolute
and we've specified a z-index of zero.

00:38:09.870 --> 00:38:13.350
The z-index will make sure that
your image appears behind the text

00:38:13.730 --> 00:38:18.790
and it allows your user to a see
the text and b select the text.

00:38:19.860 --> 00:38:24.200
And there's the CSS for our
paragraph tag down at the bottom.

00:38:24.200 --> 00:38:26.910
We've set the position to relative
and we'll show you how that

00:38:27.090 --> 00:38:31.190
allows us to do the indentation
and a margin of zero as well.

00:38:31.740 --> 00:38:34.790
So here's the CSS for the text.

00:38:34.790 --> 00:38:38.290
All the text, everything wrapped in that
paragraph tag is a font of

00:38:38.380 --> 00:38:42.360
blackout midnight set to 30 pixels,
a color of blue.

00:38:42.450 --> 00:38:45.940
And the text is positioned
70 pixels from the top,

00:38:46.050 --> 00:38:49.420
sorry 75, and 60 pixels from the left.

00:38:49.510 --> 00:38:56.300
We've also given the text a 10 degree
rotation using a CSS transform.

00:38:56.960 --> 00:39:00.090
Next, in order to get the indentation
that we see in the text,

00:39:00.420 --> 00:39:05.800
our P2 class has CSS specified
with a padding left of 60 pixels.

00:39:06.060 --> 00:39:06.990
Pretty simple, right?

00:39:07.110 --> 00:39:15.290
P3 set to a padding left of 30 pixels.

00:39:15.290 --> 00:39:15.290
So that's how we get that little
kind of stair-step-bowl pattern.

00:39:15.620 --> 00:39:17.600
All right, so that's it.

00:39:17.640 --> 00:39:20.230
That's how you lay out
your elements on your page,

00:39:20.230 --> 00:39:21.120
HTML and CSS.

00:39:21.180 --> 00:39:25.390
Now let's talk about what you
need to do in order to... Well,

00:39:25.490 --> 00:39:26.560
that's the page.

00:39:26.700 --> 00:39:27.780
Beautiful.

00:39:27.820 --> 00:39:30.040
Now let's talk about what you
have to do with your images.

00:39:30.060 --> 00:39:34.950
So I mentioned that your users
can zoom into your pages,

00:39:34.950 --> 00:39:35.840
right?

00:39:35.920 --> 00:39:41.200
Because we're rendering this as HTML,
your text will be crisp,

00:39:41.230 --> 00:39:44.200
but you also want your
images to be crisp.

00:39:44.210 --> 00:39:48.550
So we recommend that you
provide images that are one

00:39:48.550 --> 00:39:50.950
and a half times the CSS size.

00:39:51.320 --> 00:39:54.760
In the 800 by 600
example that we give you,

00:39:54.780 --> 00:39:58.790
that's images that are 1200 by 900.

00:40:00.820 --> 00:40:06.520
And the CSS will properly
shrink the image down to fit.

00:40:07.090 --> 00:40:10.900
Your images can be up
to 2 megapixels in size.

00:40:10.900 --> 00:40:14.100
So in the 4x3 example that
we've been going through,

00:40:14.300 --> 00:40:17.880
that means your images
can go up to 1600x1200.

00:40:17.980 --> 00:40:21.940
So if your user zooms in to
twice your viewport size,

00:40:22.060 --> 00:40:23.790
you're still crisp.

00:40:24.650 --> 00:40:25.710
You can use JPEGs.

00:40:25.870 --> 00:40:30.060
JPEGs will be fast and small so
your book will download faster.

00:40:30.120 --> 00:40:33.090
But if you need
transparency in your images,

00:40:33.210 --> 00:40:34.710
you can also use Pings.

00:40:35.000 --> 00:40:37.760
And we want you to use alt tags.

00:40:37.830 --> 00:40:42.270
Alt tags will allow your
images to be read to users that

00:40:42.270 --> 00:40:43.680
are using the screen reader.

00:40:43.970 --> 00:40:48.340
If they have voiceover turned on,
you want your images to be read.

00:40:48.440 --> 00:40:51.900
And remember,
if your image is worth a thousand words,

00:40:52.010 --> 00:40:54.480
your alt tag better be more than one.

00:40:57.790 --> 00:41:03.440
So, we've shown you how to set up,
layout and prepare your images

00:41:03.440 --> 00:41:05.120
for a fixed layout book.

00:41:05.420 --> 00:41:09.110
Now we're going to enhance the
same techniques that Casey showed

00:41:09.110 --> 00:41:12.840
you for embedding audio and
video in a flowing book,

00:41:12.840 --> 00:41:14.530
Work in Fixed Layout.

00:41:14.730 --> 00:41:16.880
It's all HTML5.

00:41:17.460 --> 00:41:20.720
With fixed layout books,
you can also add SVG.

00:41:20.750 --> 00:41:25.360
So if you want more advanced graphics,
you want vector graphics,

00:41:25.410 --> 00:41:27.840
that will be positioned
properly and it'll look right.

00:41:27.910 --> 00:41:30.560
When the user zooms in,
it'll still be crisp.

00:41:30.680 --> 00:41:33.160
You can also do curved text graphics.

00:41:33.240 --> 00:41:37.670
In this example of Splat the Cat,
notice the "aw" and the "hooray"

00:41:37.670 --> 00:41:39.860
all follow a curved text path.

00:41:40.080 --> 00:41:42.350
That's done with SVG.

00:41:42.910 --> 00:41:47.300
And another thing you
can do is CSS animations.

00:41:47.410 --> 00:41:53.190
So because WebKit is driving all of this,
the same CSS animations that you can

00:41:53.190 --> 00:41:56.860
use in Safari also work in books.

00:41:56.980 --> 00:42:01.480
So we're excited to see what
you can make with these things.

00:42:02.280 --> 00:42:07.310
So let's do a little summary and then I'm
going to take you through some new stuff.

00:42:07.990 --> 00:42:10.680
First, fixed layout books are EPUBs.

00:42:10.870 --> 00:42:13.460
They're the same standard
EPUBs that you use for flowing

00:42:13.460 --> 00:42:15.540
books with three additions.

00:42:15.700 --> 00:42:19.120
One, you've got to specify
the Apple display option.

00:42:19.140 --> 00:42:23.820
Two, you must specify your viewport
dimension on every page.

00:42:23.850 --> 00:42:28.060
And three, you must have a different
XHTML document per page.

00:42:28.200 --> 00:42:32.050
If you meet those three things,
you have a fixed layout book.

00:42:32.230 --> 00:42:35.140
There are some image requirements
that we talked about.

00:42:35.220 --> 00:42:39.760
Provide images that are
1.5 times the CSS size,

00:42:39.760 --> 00:42:41.880
up to 2 megapixels.

00:42:42.100 --> 00:42:45.150
And now that you have
a fixed layout book,

00:42:45.150 --> 00:42:49.350
then we open you up to a
whole world of possibilities.

00:42:50.880 --> 00:42:55.400
So today I want to talk
