00:48:08.000 --> 00:48:09.800
babysitting for you parents out there.

00:48:09.800 --> 00:48:16.230
So, alright, so without further ado,
I'm going to bring Casey back up here to

00:48:16.230 --> 00:48:19.600
show you how to make a read aloud book.

00:48:23.900 --> 00:48:25.000
Thanks Al.

00:48:25.150 --> 00:48:28.830
Oh man,
I am so excited to get to show you guys

00:48:28.830 --> 00:48:30.240
today how to make read aloud books.

00:48:30.240 --> 00:48:35.050
I think it's really special
to be able to give to WWDC the

00:48:35.200 --> 00:48:38.140
first teaching I've done of this.

00:48:38.140 --> 00:48:45.390
So, read aloud books can entirely change
the way that a kid experiences a book

00:48:45.470 --> 00:48:50.660
and we make it really easy for you to
be able to give them that experience.

00:48:50.790 --> 00:48:55.540
All you need is a fixed layout
book and a narration file.

00:48:55.620 --> 00:48:59.600
I'm going to show you today how,
go through the slides here,

00:48:59.740 --> 00:49:02.240
how you can create media overlays.

00:49:02.360 --> 00:49:06.020
This is the method of syncing
your audio with your text.

00:49:06.470 --> 00:49:10.800
Then I'll show you how you can
actually style that actively

00:49:10.840 --> 00:49:12.700
playing word using CSS.

00:49:12.790 --> 00:49:16.140
And finally,
I'll show you how you can even include

00:49:16.140 --> 00:49:18.710
an ambient soundtrack in your book.

00:49:19.480 --> 00:49:25.300
Media overlays are the EPUB3
standard for syncing audio and text.

00:49:25.300 --> 00:49:28.230
And as far as I know,
we're the first ones to do it.

00:49:28.300 --> 00:49:31.730
To create a media overlay,
you're going to want to

00:49:31.920 --> 00:49:34.370
identify the text in your HTML.

00:49:34.530 --> 00:49:39.460
You're also going to want to identify
the audio that correlates to that text.

00:49:39.520 --> 00:49:43.200
And then finally,
you need a method to pair those up.

00:49:43.330 --> 00:49:48.950
So let me first show you how
you can identify the HTML text.

00:49:49.030 --> 00:49:50.490
It's standard HTML.

00:49:50.600 --> 00:49:52.320
You're just going to include an ID.

00:49:52.410 --> 00:49:54.730
Now the granularity
for this is up to you.

00:49:54.950 --> 00:50:01.810
So you can add an ID for every word
or you can add an ID for a sentence.

00:50:01.970 --> 00:50:03.800
Entirely up to you.

00:50:03.890 --> 00:50:05.900
So now we have our text identified.

00:50:06.060 --> 00:50:11.170
Next, let's look at how you can
identify the corresponding audio.

00:50:11.660 --> 00:50:15.410
I suggest that you use an audio
editing program like Audacity.

00:50:15.700 --> 00:50:17.880
I'm suggesting Audacity
because it's free,

00:50:18.070 --> 00:50:23.100
it's cross-platform and it allows you
to not only identify the start and

00:50:23.100 --> 00:50:29.420
the end times but also add a label for
those and export it to a text document,

00:50:29.440 --> 00:50:33.490
which will make it easier
for you to include that text

00:50:33.490 --> 00:50:36.020
into your media overlay file.

00:50:36.070 --> 00:50:39.060
So,
we have our text and we have our audio,

00:50:39.060 --> 00:50:41.840
now we just need a method
to pair the two up.

00:50:41.840 --> 00:50:43.360
That is called SMILE.

00:50:43.570 --> 00:50:48.060
SMILE is the synchronized
multimedia integration language.

00:50:48.210 --> 00:50:52.710
It's just an XML file that's
used to pair text and audio and

00:50:52.900 --> 00:50:55.720
it's located in the OEBPS folder.

00:50:55.720 --> 00:50:58.210
Now I know it's been a while
since we've gone through the

00:50:58.420 --> 00:51:01.650
file structure of an EPUB,
so I'll take you back to

00:51:01.750 --> 00:51:03.560
that beautiful slide there.

00:51:03.600 --> 00:51:05.560
You can see that the OEBPS folder
is the folder that we're going

00:51:05.560 --> 00:51:05.560
to use to create our text.

00:51:05.560 --> 00:51:08.560
The OEBPS folder is the folder that
contains all of our book's content.

00:51:08.700 --> 00:51:11.990
And now,
in addition to our two EPUB XML files,

00:51:12.120 --> 00:51:16.550
the OPF and the NCX,
we're going to add SMILE files.

00:51:16.900 --> 00:52:18.500
[Transcript missing]

00:52:19.090 --> 00:52:23.650
Because you're making a new document,
you need to include all of the

00:52:23.650 --> 00:52:26.890
smile files in the book's manifest.

00:52:27.030 --> 00:52:31.350
So here's an example of
a manifest for page one.

00:52:31.530 --> 00:52:36.350
You'll see that there's page1.smile,
this is our new smile document.

00:52:36.370 --> 00:52:40.480
There's also page1.m4a,
which is the narration file.

00:52:40.480 --> 00:52:42.840
And there's page1.xhtml.

00:52:42.910 --> 00:52:45.650
Now we've added something
new to that xhtml.

00:52:45.880 --> 00:52:50.790
There's the media overlay attribute
and this acts as a cross reference

00:52:51.400 --> 00:52:58.400
so that reading systems know that the
page1 smile goes with the page1.xhtml.

00:52:58.670 --> 00:53:01.600
And that's all you need to
create a read aloud book.

00:53:01.820 --> 00:53:06.240
With the addition of the smile files,
iBooks will sync your audio and

00:53:06.320 --> 00:53:10.380
your text and will provide a
default blue highlight color so

00:53:10.380 --> 00:53:15.870
that as those words are read aloud,
the words will highlight blue.

00:53:16.380 --> 00:53:21.430
Now iBooks wants to give you guys a
way to go even above and beyond that.

00:53:21.430 --> 00:53:24.820
So I'm going to show you how you
can add your own style to those

00:53:24.870 --> 00:53:29.840
currently playing words and how you
can include a soundtrack in your book.

00:53:30.080 --> 00:53:32.970
First, I'm going to show you
how to add the style.

00:53:33.100 --> 00:53:33.730
It's easy.

00:53:33.990 --> 00:53:34.680
It's CSS.

00:53:34.780 --> 00:53:41.000
You're going to include the
CSS class -epubmedia-overlay-active.

00:53:41.640 --> 00:53:43.570
The app will style the
currently playing word.

00:53:43.600 --> 00:53:48.860
It accepts all standard CSS styling,
including color and text shadow.

00:53:48.920 --> 00:53:52.830
But do remember that the style
for it is dependent on the

00:53:52.830 --> 00:53:55.590
granularity of your HTML text IDs.

00:53:55.600 --> 00:54:01.060
So that means if you've given an
ID to each word in a sentence,

00:54:01.130 --> 00:54:05.410
each ID will light up as
the word is read aloud.

00:54:05.940 --> 00:54:11.580
However, if you put a granularity of
an ID per sentence level,

00:54:11.620 --> 00:54:14.280
that means the whole sentence
will light up while any word

00:54:14.280 --> 00:54:15.520
within it is read aloud.

00:54:15.600 --> 00:54:19.800
So for the example here,
we've put the class of "EPUB

00:54:19.800 --> 00:54:22.790
Media Overlay Active" made it red.

00:54:22.790 --> 00:54:25.620
And that just means that as
those words are read aloud,

00:54:25.620 --> 00:54:26.910
they'll turn red.

00:54:27.620 --> 00:54:29.450
Next,
I want to show you how you can include

00:54:29.450 --> 00:54:31.220
an ambient soundtrack in your book.

00:54:31.940 --> 00:54:35.480
Again, we're making this as easy
as possible because we're

00:54:35.480 --> 00:54:37.500
using the HTML audio element.

00:54:37.530 --> 00:54:42.360
And to still be cross-platform,
we are making this EPUB3

00:54:42.570 --> 00:54:48.500
compliant by adding the EPUB type
attribute of iBooks soundtrack.

00:54:48.500 --> 00:54:55.500
So, if you include this audio element in
every one of your content documents,

00:54:55.500 --> 00:54:59.550
all of your XHTML,
iBooks will know to play this audio track

00:54:59.550 --> 00:55:03.500
seamlessly across each page of your book.

00:55:03.500 --> 00:55:08.770
It's a really great way of adding some
ambiance and some style to your book and

00:55:08.840 --> 00:55:15.220
it's completely independent of the smile,
of the read aloud because it has

00:55:15.390 --> 00:55:17.500
no timestamps associated with it.

00:55:17.500 --> 00:55:18.360
So that's it.

00:55:18.500 --> 00:55:19.500
Next, iBooks Read Aloud.

00:55:19.500 --> 00:55:22.400
It's EPUB3 compliant media overlays.

00:55:22.650 --> 00:55:26.250
It allows you to style the word
highlights as you want to and you

00:55:26.450 --> 00:55:28.500
can even include a soundtrack.

